'''Aperahama Taonui''' (died 23 September 1882) was a [[New Zealand]] tribal leader, prophet, historian, teacher and assessor. He was a leader of the Te Popoto [[hapū]] of the [[Ngāpuhi]] [[iwi]]. He was born in [[Whangaroa]], [[Northland Region|Northland]], probably in the 1810s. His father was Makoare Te Taonui.<ref name="DNZB Taonui">{{DNZB|title=Aperahama Taonui|first= Judith|last= Binney|id=2t7|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref>
==The Flagstaff War== Aperahama Taonui and his father Makoare Te Taonui supported [[Tāmati Wāka Nene]] in opposing [[Hone Heke]] and [[Te Ruki Kawiti]] in the [[Flagstaff War]] (1845–46).<ref name="JC4">{{cite book |last1= Cowan |first1= James|authorlink1= |title= The New Zealand Wars: a history of the Maori campaigns and the pioneering period, Volume I: 1845–1864 |url= http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Cow01NewZ-c6.html|accessdate= |year= 1922 |publisher= R.E. Owen |location= Wellington |language= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |page=39 |pages= |chapter= Chapter 6: The Fighting at Omapere |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= |bibcode= }}</ref>
Aperahama Taonui received a bullet wound, probably in April 1845, in the [[Flagstaff War#Battle of the sticks|early fighting near Okaihau]].<ref name="DNZB Taonui"/> He was sent to Auckland to recuperate and there became friendly with Governor [[George Grey]], who awarded Aperahama Taonui a government pension.<ref name="DNZB Taonui"/> His father, Makoare Te Taonui, lead his warriors in the capture of Heke's pā at [[Te Ahuahu]],<ref name="JC4"/> which was followed by Nene's defeat of Heke in the [[Flagstaff War#Battle of Te Ahuahu|Battle of Te Ahuahu]] on 12 June 1845 at Pukenui.<ref name="nzhon2">{{cite web| title = Puketutu and Te Ahuahu - Northern War| date =3 April 2009|url= http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/war/northern-war/puketutu|publisher=Ministry for Culture and Heritage - NZ History online | accessdate=28 November 2013}}</ref><ref name="HR">{{cite book |last1= Raugh |first1= Harold E. |authorlink1= |title=The Victorians at war, 1815-1914: an encyclopedia of British military history |url= |format= |accessdate= |year= 2004 |publisher= ABC-CLIO |location= |language= |isbn=1-57607-925-2|oclc= |doi= |id= |page= |pages=225–226|chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= |bibcode= }}</ref>
