{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}
'''David Baldwin''' ( b. 22 December 1946 (?) d. 4 April 2016) was a British historian, author and former [[university lecturer]], who lived near [[Leicester]], England.<ref name=Hood/>

Baldwin specialised in late Medieval history—"the great medieval families of the [[English Midlands|Midlands]]"—and wrote several books about the people and events of the [[Wars of the Roses]].<ref name=ab/> Before retiring from teaching,<ref>{{cite web|title='What was Richard III really like?' – A new study of the last Plantagenet king|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/press-releases/2012/september/what-was-richard-iii-really-like-2019-a-new-study-of-the-last-plantagenet-king|accessdate=18 August 2013|author=University of Leicester|date=28 September 2012}}</ref> Baldwin had previously worked as a lecturer at both the [[University of Leicester]] and the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref name=ab>{{cite web|title=David Baldwin|url=http://amberleybooks.com/shop/article_9781445601823/Richard-III%3CBR%3E%3CI%3EDavid-Baldwin%3C_I%3E.html?pse=apq|accessdate=18 August 2013|author=Amberley Publishing|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110085513/http://amberleybooks.com/shop/article_9781445601823/Richard-III%3CBR%3E%3CI%3EDavid-Baldwin%3C_I%3E.html?pse=apq|archivedate=10 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1986, over 25 years before the 2012 excavation and the discovery of the king's body, he predicted that [[Exhumation of Richard III of England|Richard III's remains]] would be found at [[Greyfriars, Leicester]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New study from historian who 'predicted' whereabouts of the remains of King Richard III|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/news/blog/2012/september/30-year-old-predictions-may-be-confirmed|accessdate=18 August 2013|author=University of Leicester|date=28 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Leicester historian who predicted discovery of Richard III site in book launch|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/news/blog/2013/april/leicester-historian-who-discovered-richard-iii-site-in-book-launch|accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=Discovery>{{cite web|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/press-releases/2013/february/university-of-leicester-announces-discovery-of-king-richard-iii|title=University of Leicester announces discovery of King Richard III|publisher=University of Leicester|date=4 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leicestershire-21063882|title=Richard III dig: DNA confirms bones are king's|publisher=BBC|date=4 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burns|first=John F|title=Bones Under Parking Lot Belonged to Richard III|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/05/world/europe/richard-the-third-bones.html|accessdate=6 February 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=4 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/FINAL-RESTING-PLACE-KING/story-16893072-detail/story.html|title=Richard III dig: Eyes of world on Leicester as Greyfriars skeleton find revealed|work=[[Leicester Mercury]]|date=13 September 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208172828/http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/FINAL-RESTING-PLACE-KING/story-16893072-detail/story.html|archivedate=8 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In his 2010 book, ''Robin Hood: The English Outlaw Unmasked'', Baldwin argued  that the 'real' Robin Hood was Roger Godberd, a disinherited supporter of [[Simon de Montfort, 6th Earl of Leicester|Simon de Montfort]].<ref name=Hood>{{cite news|last=PARSONS|first=CHRIS|title=Is this the grave of Robin Hood? Historian claims farmer buried in an unmarked tomb is the outlaw behind the legend|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1372334/Has-mystery-Robin-Hoods-identity-finally-solved-Historians-claim-farmer-led-band-highwaymen.html#ixzz2cMeIjHyC|accessdate=18 August 2013|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=2 April 2011}}</ref> He drew attention to the many similarities between Godberd's career and the stories told of Robin in the earliest ballads, and to a grave slab in [[Loxley, Warwickshire|Loxley]] churchyard in Warwickshire which appeared to be identical to one associated with Robin in earlier centuries.<ref name=Hood/>

In his 2007 book, ''The Lost Prince: The Survival of Richard of York'', Baldwin discussed the possibility that the younger of the [[Princes in the Tower]], [[Richard of Shrewsbury, 1st Duke of York|Prince Richard]], survived, and was the "[[Richard Plantagenet (Richard of Eastwell)|Richard Plantagenet]]" who died in December 1550 at Eastwell in Kent. Richard had worked as a bricklayer at [[St. John's Abbey, Colchester]], until 1539, but, unusually for someone of his class, could read Latin.<ref>{{cite web|title=What happened to the Princes in the Tower?|url=http://www.le.ac.uk/ebulletin-archive/ebulletin/news/press-releases/2000-2009/2007/05/nparticle.2007-05-25.html|accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref> He is sometimes said to have been an illegitimate son of King [[Richard III]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/kent/hi/people_and_places/religion_and_ethics/newsid_8949000/8949935.stm BBC Kent: "Richard Plantagenet: Illegitimate heir's tomb in Kent?" 27 August 2010]. Accessed 5 September 2013</ref>

Baldwin was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Historical Society]] in 2012.<ref name=lmerc>{{cite news|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/historian-david-baldwin-predicted-location/story-29131131-detail/story.html|title=Historian David Baldwin who predicted the location of Richard III's Greyfriars grave dies aged 69|date=18 April 2016|work=Leicester Mercury}}</ref>

A religious man, Baldwin was a member of a [[Christadelphian]] congregation in Leicester.<ref name=lmerc/>

==Works==
Baldwin was the author of several books and contributed to a number of historical journals. In addition to teaching at Leicester and Nottingham Universities, he professionally lectured for societies and conferences.<ref name=ab/>

